title: Extraordinary [+ ddp_name +] Congress
subtitle: Even the bourgeoisie can find their way to socialism.
view-if: capital_strike_seen and not ddp_socialist and capital_strike_timer < 3 and ddp_relation >= 75 and socialism >= 60 and class_war and financing_banned and (in_weimar_coalition or in_popular_front) and pro_republic >= nationalism*2
tags: event
new-page: true
max-visits: 1

= Extraordinary [+ ddp_name +] Congress

The [+ ddp_name +] has called an extraordinary party congress to address the recent crisis with regards to the capital strike as well as the SPD's reactions to it. The party, while traditionally staunchly liberal and democratic, is nonetheless *bourgeois*-democratic, and has thus been under massive assault to oppose our project.

- @result: But they refuse to cave.

@result
on-arrival: ddp_name = "RDP"; ddp_socialist = 1; ddp_relation += socialism/10; socialism += ddp_votes; workers_ddp += socialism/10; new_middle_ddp *= (1-bourgeois_power); old_middle_ddp *= (1-bourgeois_power); rural_ddp *= (1-bourgeois_power)

With private party financing banned, the influence of business on the Democrats was already scarce, their relationship with us providing them far greater political power. Thus, in a perhaps surprising turn, they, rather than side with capital, squarely condemned capital for plunging Germany into an ever deeper recession and affirmed their unwavering support of the workers in the class war against the bourgeoisie, although many in the party still opposed this turn and have left en masse.

- @waow: Waow.

@waow
subtitle: Basedbasedbasedbasedbasedbasedbasedba
on-arrival: center_strength += 5

We have a new ally in the socialist movement!
